THE TERMS AND CONDITIONS FOR COPYING, DISTRIBUTION AND MODIFICATION

0. Definitions.

“This License” refers to version 3 of the GNU Lesser General Public License.

“The Library” means a covered work governed by this License, other than an Application or a
Combined Work as defined below.

“Covered Work” means either the unmodified Library or a work based on the Library.  Each
Covered Work, regardless of its contents, must include a copy of this License.  A work based
on the Library means either a derivative work under copyright law or a work that is designed
to work with the Library (e.g. by being compiled or linked with it).  (Hereinafter, “work based
on the Library” shall be treated as equivalent to a “derivative work”.)

An “Application” is any work that makes use of an interface provided by the Library, but which is
not by itself a derivative of the Library.  (For example, a program that simply links to a
library below the threshold of being a derivative work is an Application, not a Combined Work.)

A “Combined Work” is a work produced by combining or linking an Application with the Library.
The particular version of the Library with which a Combined Work was made is also called the
“Linked Version”.

The “Minimal Corresponding Source” for a Combined Work means the Corresponding Source for
the Combined Work, excluding any source code for portions of the Combined Work that, considered
in isolation, are not derived from the Library, and can be reasonably regarded as independent
modules of the Combined Work.

The “Corresponding Application Code” for a Combined Work means the object code and/or source
code for the Application, including any data and utility programs needed for reproducing the
Combined Work from its source code, but excluding the Library and its individual modules.

“Installation Information” for a Combined Work means any methods, procedures, authorization
keys, or other information required to install and execute a modified version of the Combined
Work from a modified version of its Minimal Corresponding Source.

1. Exception to Section 3 of the GNU General Public License.
You may convey a covered work under sections 3 and 4 of this License without being bound by
section 3 of the GNU General Public License.  An uncombined work that is a library, or is
derived from a library, is not a Combined Work.

2. Conveying Modified Versions.
You may modify your copy or copies of the Library or any portion of it, thus forming a work
based on the Library, and copy and distribute such modifications under the terms of Section 4
above, provided that you also meet all of these conditions:
    a) The modifications are themselves covered by this License, and the entire work, as a
        whole, is licensed at no charge to all third parties under the terms of this License.
    b) You must cause the modified files to carry prominent notices stating that you changed the
        files and the date of any change.
    c) If a facility in the modified Library refers to a function or data to be supplied by an
        Application that uses the facility, then you must make a good-faith effort to ensure that,
        in the event an Application does not supply such function or data, the facility still operates,
        and performs in a manner as close as reasonably possible to the mode of operation it would
        have had if such function or data had been supplied.
    d) If you link the Library with a modified version of it to form a Combined Work, you must
        provide complete corresponding source for the modified portions of the Library in a form
        suitable for further modification, and that must be distributed under the terms of Section 4.

3. Conveying Non-Source Forms.
You may convey a covered work in object code form under the terms of Sections 4 and 5, provided
that you also convey the Minimal Corresponding Source under the terms of this License, or that you,
if the conveying occurs solely by offering access to copy from a designated place, offer to provide
the Minimal Corresponding Source there.  “Convey” means any kind of propagation that enables
other parties to make or receive copies.  The term “copy” as used in this License includes both
verbatim and modified copies.

4. Combined Works.
You may convey a Combined Work under terms of your choice that, taken together, effectively
restrict modification of the portions of the Library contained in the Combined Work and
reverse engineering for debugging such modifications, if you also do each of the following:
    a) Give prominent notice with each copy of the Combined Work that the Library is used in it
        and that the Library and its use are covered by this License.
    b) Accompany the Combined Work with a copy of the GNU Lesser General Public License.
    c) For a Combined Work that displays a user interface, provide a means for the user to obtain
        the Minimal Corresponding Source of the Library.
    d) Do one of the following:
            0) Convey the Minimal Corresponding Source of the Library in a physical product
                (e.g. on a CD accompanying the Combined Work), or,
            1) Convey the Minimal Corresponding Source of the Library via network server a long
                distance accessible by means that are appropriate for the medium, or,
            2) Convey individual copies of the Minimal Corresponding Source in a machine-readable
                medium suitable for reproducibility.
    e) Provide Installation Information, but only if you would otherwise be required to provide
        such information under Section 6 of the GNU General Public License, and only to the extent
        that such information is necessary to install and execute a modified version of the Combined
        Work produced by recombining or linking the Library with a modified version of it.

5. Combined Interfaces.
A “Combined Work” need not use a single, monolithic Interface between the Library and the
Application.  Rather, the Library may be supplemented with multiple smaller interfaces that,
taken together, constitute an integrated whole.  Each such separate interface is covered by this
License in the same manner as the Library, though a particular interface may be made subject to
additional permissions.

6. Termination.
If you violate any provision of this License, your rights under it terminate automatically.
However, parties who have received copies, or rights, from you under this License will not have
their licenses terminated so long as such parties remain in full compliance.  If you cease all
violation of this License, your license from a particular copyright holder is reinstated (a)
provisionally, unless and until termination is expressly notified, and (b) permanently, if the
copyright holder fails to notify you of any violation within 60 days after your cessation.

